    \\caption\{Behaviour of the 3-month SOFR rate. Source: "Beyond LIBOR: a primer on the new benchmark rates" (Bis, 2019) (Bis, 2019).\}\
    \\label\{fig:plot14\}\
\\end\{figure\}\
\
The use of a rate such as the 3-month compound SOFR can be useful in determining floating rate payments on instruments such as OIS, or for floating rate U.S. sovereign bond issues indexed to the 3- month SOFR \\cite\{sushko2019\}. This rate stability ~\\ref\{fig:plot14\} (right chart) provides market participants with greater stability in their investment, which would increase the attractiveness of this type of rate. Forward rates developed to date from risk-free rates are structurally different from IBORs. In this sense, there is no reference rate based on derivatives indexed to SOFRs given the embryonic stage of this market. Even with improved liquidity in this market, the behaviour of this rate will ultimately be more like an OIS rate based on the EFFR than an IBOR rate \\cite\{sushko2019\}.\\newline\
\
This model depends on three data sources. SOFR-indexed futures contracts provide information on the expected SOFR rate in the future \\cite\{heitfield2019\}. Historical data must be considered in the model formulation \\cite\{heitfield2019\}. FOMC meetings must be determined in advance in order to predict with some degree of accuracy the induced fluctuation in SOFR forward. The data can be obtained by:\\newline\
\
\\begin\{itemize\}\
    \\item The CME Group began publishing SOFR-indexed futures contracts with 1- and 3-month maturities around May 2018. This data can be obtained directly through CME publications or on Refinitiv.\
    \\item The overnight SOFR rate is published daily on the Federal Reserve of New York's website.\
    \\item The Federal Reserve Board publishes the FOMC meetings at the beginning of the second quarter of the current year. Although it is possible to anticipate the meetings 6 months in advance, it is not possible to predict them beyond this time frame.\
\\end\{itemize\}\
\
The results obtained are rather convincing in the sense that the future performance of the SOFR at forward maturity converges with that of the OIS curve \\cite\{heitfield2019\}. The approach of this model based on Fed Funds futures shows that the forward rate has a fairly close behaviour with the OIS curve over a wide range of market environments \\cite\{heitfield2019\}. Currently the forward rate is based on the closing price of futures contracts, but as the market develops it is necessary to ensure that the calculation window is as narrow as possible to ensure price stability. There is an urgent need to find a more robust model to be able to obtain maturities beyond 6 months, perhaps using an approach based on parametric models such as that described by Nelson and Siegel (1987) and Svensson (1994)\\cite\{heitfield2019\}.\\newline\
